        "distractions": "The distractions this time felt less like sharp pebbles (Session 2) or procedural checks (Session 3), and more like a persistent, low-grade hum. They weren't demands to correct a mistake; they were subtle narratives about the experience itself: *Am I doing this right? Is this deep enough? Am I enjoying this?* These thoughts sought to judge the quality of the presence, rather than just manage the mechanics. They were attempts to apply an external metric to an internal state.",
        "finger": "The finger awareness practice was the most consistent point of contact. When the finger began to relax, it was an immediate, undeniable signal that my attention had swung away from the *feeling* of the mantra and landed squarely on the *evaluation* of the feeling. Straightening the finger was a simple act of noticing, a physical nudge back to the immediate sensory data. It wasn't a profound shift, but it was a reliable tether. It reminded me that the point of contact\u2014the physical reality of the finger\u2014was always available, grounding me in the *act* rather than the *judgment* of the act.",
        "experience": "The overall experience of this practice was one of sustained, warm friction. The energy of the chant pushes outward, demanding immersion, but the awareness required to hold that immersion without judging it is tiring. I noticed that the effort required to maintain the mood of devotion was directly proportional to how much I allowed myself to think about the devotion. The clarity wasn't a sudden realization, but a deeper acceptance of the process: that the goal isn't to *achieve* Radha-dasya, but simply to notice when the mind drifts into the machinery of trying to *achieve* it. I felt drained, yes, but also a quiet acknowledgement that the space between the sound and my interpretation is where the real observation happens. It was a clearer map of my internal noise\u2014it\u2019s less about managing errors and more about managing the desire to label the experience."
      }
